          "body": "Verses 5-6 deliver the chapter's theological payload. Those who made Cush their 'hope' (*mabbat* — the object you look toward for rescue) and Egypt their 'boast' (*tipharah* — beauty, glory) will be 'dismayed and ashamed' (*chatat* and *bush*). The word pair is covenantal: Jeremiah uses it repeatedly for the collapse of false trusts (Jeremiah 2:36; 17:13); the Psalms use *bush* for the shame that falls on those who trust in anything other than the LORD (Psalm 25:3; 31:1). Isaiah's theology of trust is not abstract piety but a structural claim: the human heart was designed to repose its weight on the LORD, and when it transfers that weight to a created power — no matter how impressive — it will eventually bear the shame of that transfer. Egypt is the chapter's example, but the principle is universal. As Tim Keller framed the same dynamic: anything we use as a functional savior will eventually either be taken from us or revealed as unable to bear the weight we have placed on it."
