          "body": "The chapter closes not with a verdict but with a question: 'How shall we escape?' (20:6). The inhabitants of the coastland have watched their hope (Egypt) collapse and are now face to face with the Assyrian threat without a shield. The question is left open in the text — Isaiah does not answer it in chapter 20. This is deliberate. The answer has been Isaiah's sustained argument from chapters 1 through 19: the only escape is through the LORD, not through Egypt (cf. Isaiah 8:13-14; 30:15: 'In repentance and rest you will be saved; in quietness and trust is your strength'). The unanswered question forces the reader — ancient Judahite and contemporary student alike — to supply the answer themselves, which is the moment of personal application. The coastland's question is the reader's question. Their Egypt is whatever human power I have substituted for trusting the living God. The chapter does not answer because only the reader can name what their Egypt is."
