        "title": "The sign commanded — God speaks through a body, not only a voice",
        "range": "20:1-2",
        "excerpt": "At that time the LORD spoke through Isaiah the son of Amoz, saying, 'Go and loosen the sackcloth from your hips and take your shoes off your feet.' And he did so, going naked and barefoot.",
        "body": "The dateline of verse 1 situates the chapter inside a specific political crisis. Sargon II of Assyria (722–705 BC) had consolidated his empire after destroying Samaria in 722 BC (2 Kings 17:6) and was now pressing westward. Ashdod, a Philistine city that had rebelled against Assyrian tribute, was crushed. The anti-Assyrian coalition that Egypt was bankrolling had just lost its most visible member. For the political counselors in Jerusalem — described in Isaiah 30:1-5 as those who 'take refuge in the safety of Pharaoh' — this was a moment of either panic or doubled-down commitment to the Egyptian strategy. Isaiah's commission arrives at precisely this moment.\n\nThe command is without diplomatic softening: remove the sackcloth, remove the sandals, walk. The sackcloth is significant. It was the standard garment of prophetic intercession and mourning — Elijah wore hair-cloth (2 Kings 1:8), Isaiah had been wearing it as he mourned for Israel and prayed for Judah. Even the garment of grief is now taken away; there is no covering left, literal or symbolic. What remains is the prophet's bare body as the message. This is not the only prophetic sign-act in Isaiah's ministry (cf. Isaiah 8:1-4, the naming of his son Maher-shalal-hash-baz as a sign), but it is the most physically costly and the most sustained.\n\nThe phrase 'the LORD spoke through Isaiah' is literally 'the LORD spoke by the hand of Isaiah' (*be-yad yeshayah*) — an idiom used throughout the historical books for the transmission of prophetic commands (1 Kings 16:12; 2 Kings 9:36; 14:25). The medium is always human; the authority is always divine. Isaiah's naked body on the streets of Jerusalem does not originate in prophetic self-expression but in divine commission.\n\nThe obedience is total and immediate: 'he did so.' There is no recorded hesitation, negotiation, or complaint. John Calvin's commentary on this passage (Opera Omnia) notes that the speed of compliance is itself part of the prophetic witness — Isaiah's willing self-humiliation demonstrates that the LORD's word has authority over every zone of life, including the prophet's own social dignity.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Be-yad* (by the hand of) — the standard idiom for prophetic mediation throughout Kings and Chronicles. *Saq* (sackcloth) — coarse, dark goat-hair fabric; mourning garment. *Arom* (naked) — unclothed, stripped; in legal and prophetic texts consistently associated with vulnerability and shame (Genesis 3:7; Ezekiel 16:37). *Yacheph* (barefoot) — without sandals; in 2 Samuel 15:30 David goes barefoot in mourning; here the absence of sandals signifies subjugation."
