        "range": "20:3",
        "excerpt": "And the LORD said, 'Even as My servant Isaiah has gone naked and barefoot three years as a sign and token against Egypt and Cush...'",
        "body": "Verse 3 is the interpretive key the chapter provides for itself, and its weight cannot be overstated. The LORD does not leave the sign's meaning open to popular interpretation. He names the duration (three years), the classification (sign and token — *ot u-mophet*), and the referent (Egypt and Cush). Each element carries theological freight.\n\nThe three-year duration is extraordinary. Prophetic sign-acts in the Old Testament are typically brief — Jeremiah buries a linen belt (Jeremiah 13:1-11), Ezekiel lies on his side for 390 days (Ezekiel 4:4-8). Three years of sustained daily performance is exceptional. It means that every person in Jerusalem who saw Isaiah over a three-year period saw the prophecy walking. There was no escape from the message, no capacity to forget it between dramatic performances. The sign achieved what a spoken oracle could not: inescapable, daily presence.\n\nThe pairing of *ot* (sign) and *mophet* (omen, wonder) is a fixed formula in the covenant vocabulary of the Pentateuch. In Deuteronomy 28:46 the same pairing describes the consequences of covenant disobedience: 'They shall be a sign and a wonder on you and your descendants forever.' In Exodus 7:3 the LORD says He will multiply His signs and wonders (*otot u-mophetim*) in Egypt. Isaiah 20:3 deliberately invokes both uses: the sign is structured as both a Deuteronomic covenant warning and a reversal of the Exodus signs. Egypt, which once suffered the LORD's signs against it, is now the target of a new sign — and the reversal is complete: Exodus signs delivered Israel *from* Egypt; Isaiah's sign announces that Egypt itself will be led away captive.\n\nThe title 'My servant' (*avdi*) is one of Isaiah's most loaded designations. It appears throughout the servant songs of Isaiah 40-55 (42:1; 49:3; 50:10; 52:13; 53:11) and anchors Isaiah's own role within a broader pattern of suffering obedience that ultimately points toward the Servant who bears shame vicariously. That the LORD calls Isaiah 'My servant' at the moment of his maximum public humiliation is the chapter's most theologically resonant moment: the servant's obedient nakedness is the vehicle through which the LORD speaks.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Ot u-mophet* (sign and omen) — fixed covenant formula: Exodus 7:3; Deuteronomy 13:1-2; 28:46; Psalm 78:43. *Avdi* (My servant) — the Isaianic servant designation; also used of Moses (Numbers 12:7), David (2 Samuel 7:5), and the Suffering Servant of Isaiah 52-53. *Shalosh shanim* (three years) — the only prophetic sign-act in the canonical prophets prescribed for exactly three years."
