        "excerpt": "So the king of Assyria will lead away the captives of Egypt and the exiles of Cush, young and old, naked and barefoot with buttocks uncovered, to the shame of Egypt.",
        "body": "The 'so' that opens verse 4 performs the chapter's central logical move: it maps Isaiah's sign onto its fulfillment with explicit semantic correspondence. As the prophet walked — so the captives will walk. The verb *nahag* (to drive, lead) is used elsewhere of herding animals (Genesis 31:18; 1 Samuel 23:5), which sharpens the dehumanizing force of the image: Egypt's people will be driven like livestock by the Assyrian army.\n\nThe specificity of verse 4 is historically confirmable. Assyrian palace reliefs from Sennacherib's palace at Nineveh and Esarhaddon's victory steles depict exactly this: captive populations marched in degrading conditions, stripped of clothing and dignity, led on leashes or in chains. Ancient Near Eastern military propaganda regularly displayed captive populations in this manner as evidence of divine approval of the conquering king. Isaiah is not employing metaphor; he is predicting that Egypt will become the subject of the very propaganda imagery its own alliance partners have been consuming from Assyrian diplomatic communications.\n\nThe phrase 'young and old alike' removes every demographic exemption. The young did not choose the policy; they will share its consequences. The old who argued for the Egyptian alliance will not be spared by age. This is a comprehensive national judgment, not a targeted political purge. The concluding phrase — 'to the shame of Egypt' (*le-ervat mitsrayim*) — uses *ervah*, the strongest Hebrew word for shameful nakedness, the same word used in Leviticus 18 for sexual exposure and in Genesis 9:22-23 for Ham's exposure of Noah. Egypt's fall will not merely be a military defeat; it will be a public humiliation on the scale that *ervah* vocabulary conveys.\n\nThe historical fulfillment unfolded in stages. Assyria under Esarhaddon sacked Memphis in 671 BC and Ashurbanipal sacked Thebes (No-Amon) in 663 BC — events Isaiah 19 and Nahum 3:8-10 both reference. The complete humiliation of Egypt and Cush as a geopolitical unit was accomplished by Babylon under Nebuchadnezzar (605-568 BC). Peter Craigie (*Old Testament Theology*) and John Oswalt (*The Book of Isaiah, Chapters 1-39*, NICOT) both note that the Babylonian period, not merely Assyria, represents the full execution of Isaiah's prophecy against Egypt.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Nahag* (to lead/drive) — the herding verb; cf. Psalm 80:1, where the LORD 'leads Joseph like a flock.' *Arom ve-yacheph* (naked and barefoot) — the full pairing of the sign-vocabulary; the fulfillment lexically mirrors the sign. *Le-ervat mitsrayim* (to Egypt's shame/nakedness) — *ervah* is Levitical nakedness/shame vocabulary; its use here marks Egypt's defeat as total, public dishonor."
