        "excerpt": "Then they will be dismayed and ashamed because of Cush their hope and Egypt their boast... 'How shall we escape?'",
        "body": "Verses 5-6 execute the chapter's pastoral purpose. The emotional vocabulary is carefully chosen. *Chatat* (dismayed, shattered) describes the psychological collapse of a defense — it is used in military contexts for the shattering of a battle line (1 Samuel 17:11; Isaiah 31:9) and in covenantal contexts for the breaking of the heart that trusted in something that has failed (Jeremiah 17:18). *Bush* (ashamed) is the covenant word for the exposure of misplaced trust — it appears in Isaiah 1:29, 20:5, 30:5, and 31:1, forming a sustained Isaianic argument that every form of political idolatry ends in *bush*. Together the pair describes not mere disappointment but the total psychological and social collapse of those whose security has been revealed as illusory.\n\nThe phrase 'because of Cush their hope and Egypt their boast' is the chapter's most precise theological diagnosis. Hope (*mabbat*) is what you look toward for rescue — the direction of your gaze in a crisis. Boast (*tipharah*) is what you parade as your glory, your strongest card. Egypt had been both: the military hope and the pride of the coalition. When Egypt is stripped naked, the nations who staked everything on it experience not only military exposure but theological exposure — their functional savior has been revealed as unable to save.\n\nThe closing rhetorical question of verse 6 — 'How shall we escape?' — is the chapter's most remarkable move. Isaiah does not answer it. The question hangs in the air, unanswered, and the reader must supply the response. The answer the book of Isaiah provides across its 66 chapters is consistent: 'In repentance and rest you will be saved; in quietness and trust is your strength' (30:15). 'Those who trust in the LORD will gain new strength' (40:31). 'Look to Me and be saved, all the ends of the earth; for I am God, and there is no other' (45:22). The question of 20:6 is the opening through which the whole Isaianic theology of trust flows. As D. A. Carson has noted in his discussions of Isaiah's theology of faith, the prophetic literature consistently posits that the only genuine escape from imperial threat is the reorientation of national and individual trust from created powers back to the Creator.\n\nThe Reformed tradition (Calvin, Edwards, Owen) reads this passage as confirming the utter inadequacy of all human strength as a ground of salvation — a principle that extends from geopolitics to soteriology. Egypt is the macro-scale example; but the same structure operates wherever any human being substitutes a created resource for the living God. Arminian readers agree on the substance: misplaced trust is universally condemned; the LORD alone is the proper object of hope. The distinction is not here but in the question of whether the reorientation of trust is itself a divine gift or a human decision enabled by prevenient grace — a question Isaiah 20 does not settle but which the broader Isaianic corpus raises acutely (cf. Isaiah 53:6; 55:1-3).\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chatat* (dismayed, shattered) — root of the word for *sin* in some contexts; here the breaking of a battle line or a defense. *Bush* (ashamed) — the covenant shame of exposed misplaced trust; appears 6× in Isaiah's oracles against Egypt and its allies. *Mabbat* (hope, object of looking) — from *nabat*, to look; hope is always about the direction of your gaze. *Tipharah* (boast, glory) — the same word used for the LORD's glory in Isaiah 28:5; here applied to Egypt, which is the chapter's sharpest irony."
